, snake with rooster's head and feet and bat's wings\n* [[Dragon]], European and East Asian reptile-like mythical creature\n* [[Griffin]] or griffon, lion-bird hybrid\n* [[Harpy]], Greco-Roman mythological bird monster with woman's face\n* [[Siren (mythology)|Siren]], Greco-Roman mythical creature with the combined features of a woman and bird, often a woman's head and breasts and a bird's body \n* [[Lamassu]], Assyrian deity, bull/lion-eagle-human hybrid\n* [[Manticore]], Persian monster with a lion's body and a humanoid head.\n* [[Nue]], Japanese legendary creature\n* [[Pegasus]], winged stallion in Greek mythology\n* [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix]], self-regenerating bird in Greek mythology\n* [[Pixiu]] or Pi Yao, Chinese mythical creature\n* [[Qilin]], Chinese/East Asian mythical hybrid creature\n* [[Sharabha]], Hindu mythology: lion-bird hybrid\n* [[Simurgh]], Iranian mythical flying creature\n* [[Sirin]], Russian mythological creature, half-woman half-bird\n* [[Snow Lion]], Tibetan mythological celestial animal\n* [[Yali (Hindu mythology)|Yali]], Hindu mythological lion-elephant-horse hybrid\n* [[Ziz]], giant griffin-like bird in Jewish mythology\n* [[Komainu]] to compare its use in Japanese culture\n* [[Chinthe]] similar lion statues in Burma, Laos and Cambodia\n* [[Shisa]] similar lion statues in the Ryukyu Islands\n* [[Nian]] to compare with a similar but horned (unicorn) mythical beast\n* [[Haetae]] to compare with similar lion-like statues in [[Korea]].\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* Clay, Jenny Strauss, ''Hesiod's Cosmos'', Cambridge University Press, 2003. {{ISBN|978-0-521-82392-0}}.\n* Stewart, Desmond. Pyramids and the Sphinx. [S.l.]: ''Newsweek'', U.S., 72. Print.\n* {{Cite web|url = https://jfava.ut.ac.ir/article_30063.html|title = Gopat (Sphinx) and Shirdal (Gryphon) in the Ancient Middle East|date = 2013|publisher = Tehran: Honarhay-e Ziba Journal, Vol. 17, No. 4|last = Taheri|first = Sadreddin}}\n* Kallich, Martin. \"Oedipus and the Sphinx.\" ''Oedipus: Myth and Drama''. N.p.: Western, 1968. N. pag. Print.\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Dessenne, Andr\u00e9. ''Le Sphinx: \u00c9tude iconographique'' (in French). De Boccard, 1957.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141127153327/http://www.newslobby.net/2014/10/23/historical-moment-sphinx-head-found-in-greek-tomb/ Sphinx Head Found in Greek Tomb]\n* [http://www.life.com/image/first/in-gallery/51921/the-sphinx-totally-random-trivia The Sphinx: Totally Random Trivia] - slideshow by ''[[Life magazine]]''\n\n{{Ancient Egyptian religion footer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient Egyptian symbols]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek art]]\n[[Category:Egyptian artefact types]]\n[[Category:Egyptian legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Fantasy creatures]]\n[[Category:Greek legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Horned deities]]\n[[Category:Human-headed mythical creatures]]\n[[Category:Monsters in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Mythological hybrids]]\n[[Category:Mythological lions]]\n[[Category:Mythological monsters]]\n[[Category:Riddles]]\n", "name_user": "Paul August", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphinx"}
{"title_page": "Lee Fierro", "text_new": "'''Elizabeth Lee Fierro''',<ref name=weiss20/> better known as '''Lee Fierro''' (February 13, 1929 \u2013 April 5, 2020), was an American actress best known as playing Mrs. Kintner  in the ''[[Jaws_(franchise)|Jaws]]'' film franchise. She lived for many years on [[Martha's Vineyard]], where from 1974 to 2017 she was artistic director of the Island Theatre Workshop.<ref name=vg17>{{cite news |last1=Anonymous |title=Three Cheers, Bon Voyage for Lee Fierro |url=https://vineyardgazette.com/news/2017/06/01/three-cheers-bon-voyage-lee-fierro |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Vineyard Gazette - Martha's Vineyard News |date=1 June 2017 |language=en}}</ref> She died in 2020 of [[COVID-19]].<ref name=\"brennan20\">{{cite news |last1=Brennan |first1=George |title=Lee Fierro, \u2018fiercely dedicated\u2019 to theater, has died |url=https://www.mvtimes.com/2020/04/05/lee-fierro-fiercely-dedicated-theater-died/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Martha's Vineyard Times |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=alexander20>{{cite news |last1=Alexander |first1=Bryan |title='Jaws' actress Lee Fierro, whose Mrs. Kintner slapped Chief Brody, dies of coronavirus at 91 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/movies/2020/04/05/jaws-actress-lee-fierro-mrs-kintner-slaps-chief-brody-dies/2952350001/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=moreau20>{{cite news |last1=Moreau |first1=Jordan |title=Lee Fierro, \u2018Jaws\u2019 Actor, Dies of Coronavirus at 91 |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/lee-fierro-jaws-dead-dies-coronavirus-1234571541/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=Variety |date=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=weiss20>{{cite news |last1=Weiss |first1=Josh |title=Lee Fierro, Mrs. Kintner is Steven Spielberg's 'Jaws,' dies at 91 from coronavirus complications |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/lee-fierro-mrs-kintner-in-jaws-dies-at-91 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=SYFY WIRE |date=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 she received a \"Woman of the Year\" award by Women Empowered to Make Healthy Choices for her local theater workshop.<ref name=teawithlee17>{{cite news |last1=Anonymous |title=Farewell \u201cTea with Lee\u201d for Lee Fierro |url=https://www.mvtimes.com/2017/05/31/farewell-tea-lee-lee-fierro/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Martha's Vineyard Times |date=31 May 2017}}</ref> \nHer famous ''Jaws'' scene required several \"takes\".<ref name=garrett14>{{cite news |last1=Garrett |first1=Major |title=40 years later \"Jaws\" still alive on Martha's Vineyard |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/40-years-later-jaws-still-alive-on-marthas-vineyard/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=www.cbsnews.com |date=1 September 2014 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0276444}}\n\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "'''Elizabeth Lee Fierro''',<ref name=weiss20/> better known as '''Lee Fierro''' (February 13, 1929 \u2013 April 5, 2020), was an actress best known as playing Mrs. Kintner  in the ''[[Jaws_(franchise)|Jaws]]'' film franchise. She lived for many years on [[Martha's Vineyard]], where from 1974 to 2017 she was artistic director of the Island Theatre Workshop.<ref name=vg17>{{cite news |last1=Anonymous |title=Three Cheers, Bon Voyage for Lee Fierro |url=https://vineyardgazette.com/news/2017/06/01/three-cheers-bon-voyage-lee-fierro |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Vineyard Gazette - Martha's Vineyard News |date=1 June 2017 |language=en}}</ref> She died in 2020 of [[COVID-19]].<ref name=\"brennan20\">{{cite news |last1=Brennan |first1=George |title=Lee Fierro, \u2018fiercely dedicated\u2019 to theater, has died |url=https://www.mvtimes.com/2020/04/05/lee-fierro-fiercely-dedicated-theater-died/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Martha's Vineyard Times |date=5 April 2